  "prompt": "How do I find the average acceleration?",
  "response": "To find the average acceleration of an object, you can use the following formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Average Acceleration} = \\frac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\(\\Delta v\\) is the change in velocity (final velocity \\(-\\) initial velocity).\n- \\(\\Delta t\\) is the change in time (final time \\(-\\) initial time).\n\n### Step-by-Step Process:\n1. **Determine the initial velocity (\\(v_i\\))** and **final velocity (\\(v_f\\))** of the object.\n2. Calculate the change in velocity (\\(\\Delta v\\)):\n   \\[\n   \\Delta v = v_f - v_i\n   \\]\n3. Determine the initial time (\\(t_i\\)) and **final time (\\(t_f\\))**.\n4. Calculate the change in time (\\(\\Delta t\\)):\n   \\[\n   \\Delta t = t_f - t_i\n   \\]\n5. Plug the values into the formula for average acceleration:\n   \\[\n   \\text{Average Acceleration} = \\frac{v_f - v_i}{t_f - t_i}\n   \\]\n\n### Units:\n- Acceleration is typically measured in meters per second squared (\\(m/s^2\\)).\n\n### Example:\nSuppose a car accelerates from \\(20 \\, m/s\\) to \\(50 \\, m/s\\) in \\(5 \\, seconds\\).\n\n\\[\n\\Delta v = 50 \\, m/s - 20 \\, m/s = 30 \\, m/s\n\\]\n\\[\n\\Delta t = 5 \\, s\n\\]\n\\[\n\\text{Average Acceleration} = \\frac{30 \\, m/s}{5 \\, s} = 6 \\, m/s^2\n\\]\n\nThus, the average acceleration is \\(6 \\, m/s^2\\).",
